analysis: The unemployment numbers in Total Nonfarm only bump up in two places: around 2001 and around 2008. These two dips are explained by the economic crisis of those times. In the early 2000s, the dot com crash hit the tech sector hard. In 2007 and 2008, the housing sector crashed, resulting in the near collapse of the economy. The unemployment rates then recovered starting in 2009, increasing 27% between 2009 and 2020. Total Nonfarm makes up a large piece of the total unemployment in New York City because it contains the largest category of industries within it.

The unemployment numbers in Total Private, like in Total Nonfarm only dip in two places: around 2001 and around 2008. These two dips are explained by the economic crisis of those times. In the early 2000s, the dot com crash hit the tech sector hard. In 2007 and 2008, the housing sector crashed, resulting in the near collapse of the economy. The unemployment rates then recover from 2010 onwards, increasing 29% between 2010 and 2020. Total Private makes up the second largest piece of unemployment numbers and follows the same trends as Total Nonfarm.

The goods production industry has been on the steady decline from 1998 to 2011. Interestingly enough, the dot com crash did not really affect the goods production industry. In fact, from 1998 to 2001 the industry actually strengthened. This may be because not many of the internet companies that went bankrupt during the crisis were actually based in New York, despite providing their services to its citizens. The decline beginning in 2001 was most likely caused by the closure of many of New York City’s factories. The industry never recovered to its 1999 levels despite its climb starting in 2011, with its employment rate in 2020 being only 76% of the employment rate in 1998. The industry was hit hard during the beginning of the pandemic but has since recovered to about 88% of what it was. This industry follows the trend that many other industries follow, with its employment numbers generally following the different crises.

Although the service industry follows the same general trends as many other industries, it has been steadily strengthening for about 20 years. The crisis in 2008-9 only briefly halted the industry’s climb and it was not at all affected by the dot com crash in 2001. Between 1998 and 2020, the employment numbers increased 36%. The industry was hit hard during the pandemic and is now only at 88% of what it once was.

The Natural Resources, Mining, and Construction industry follows the same patterns as many other industries do. It is interesting to note though that the industry was affected more by the dot com crash in the early 2000s than it was during the COVID-19 pandemic. During the early 2000s, nearly 10% of industry workers lost their jobs while around 8% lost their jobs during the first few months of COVID-19.

Manufacturing has been on a heavy decline since 1998. The decline was accelerated by the economic crisis in 2008 and in 2000 like most industries. Now, the industry is at 34% employment compared to what it was during 1998. During the first few months of COVID-19, the industry dropped to about 80% of what it was beforehand.

The Trade, Transportation, and Utilities industries follow the same trends as many other industries, peaking in early 2000, and in 2019. The industry seemed to have large problems during 2003 and 2004, which could have been caused by some sort of legislation that made it much harder to trade out of New York City. The industry was hit much harder during the early 2000s, however, with employment dropping 7% between 2001 and 2003 compared to 4% between 2008 and 2009. During the first few months of COVID-19, the industry experienced an 11% drop in employment.

The retail industry follows the same patterns as many other industries do with the industry suffering during the dot com crash, the crash of 2008 and during COVID-19. The industry recovered more than many other industries during COVID-19, only dropping 7% in employment.

The Transportation, Warehousing, and Utilities industry has suffered a lot over the years, following the same trends as many other industries. The employment numbers dropped a lot during the dot com crash and during the housing crisis but steadily climbed afterwards until the COVID-19 pandemic. From the end of the housing crisis until 2019, the industry recovered nearly 24%. During the COVID-19 pandemic, the numbers dropped about 8%.

The information industry, like many other industries, was affected heavily by the housing crisis and the dot-com crash. When the dot-com bubble burst in 2001, employment dropped 21%. The industry slowly struggled to recover until 2010, when it began to grow again. The industry was not hit that hard by the pandemic, however, dropping only 2% during the pandemic’s first few months.

The information industry, like many other industries, was affected heavily by the housing crisis and the dot-com crash. When the dot-com bubble burst in 2001, employment dropped 14%. The industry recovered until the housing crisis, when it dropped 8%. During the COVID-19 pandemic, the unemployment rate in the finance industry was hit hard and did not really recover, dropping another 6%.

Although the Professional and Business Services industry was hit during the dot com crash and the housing crisis, it has overall grown about 50% between 1998 and 2020. Between 2010 and 2019, employment grew 40%. During the pandemic, however, the industry suffered, dropping nearly 12%.

The number of people employed in Education has consistently increased since 1998. As expected, every year following May, there is a decrease in the number of people employed in Educational Services. For example, in 2001 from May to June, employment dropped from 15,580 to 13,230. However, every year by September, the number of employed people returns to its value prior to Summer.

Health Care and Social Assistance has been growing since 1998 and has been mostly unaffected by crises, besides Covid-19. Despite Health Care’s importance in solving the Covid-19 crisis, employment numbers dropped from 82,230 to 72,410 just from March to April. Although this is a much less significant drop than in some other industries, such as Leisure and Hospitality, it is still surprising that the number of people employed in healthcare decreased during a pandemic.

Similar to many other industries, Leisure and Hospitality has been steadily growing since 1998, almost doubling its size in the past two decades. As one could expect due to the lack of travel to New York over the past year, Covid-19 severely impacted the Leisure and Hospitality industry. The number of employed people went from 41,540 to 14,800, a 64% decrease. It has also been slow to recover, as travel has not significantly rebounded.

The number of people employed in the Accommodation and Food Services industry has doubled since 1998. The industry was not affected severely by the financial crisis, but its employment numbers dropped from 32,920 to 11,390 following the pandemic. This demonstrates the extent to which Covid-19 impacted the Accommodation and Food Services industry.

Other Services is one of the least volatile industries. Throughout the past several decades, it has been steadily increasing in employment numbers, and it was not affected that severely by any crises with the exception of Covid-19. From March to April, employment dropped from 19,490 to 13,710, and even now, employment numbers remain 30 thousand lower than they were prior to the pandemic.

Throughout the past several decades within government, the number of employed people has been slowly rising. However, around the start of Summer, employment numbers usually drop, especially in the late 1990’s and early 2000’s. During the 2008 Financial Crisis, Government employment numbers were not affected that severely. The Government industry was hit hard by Covid-19, as employment numbers dropped from 59,590 to 51,190 from March to June. However, relative to other industries, it had a fairly quick recovery. By August, employment numbers were matching those at the start of the pandemic.
